","1145":"1145","1112":"1112","1145?":"1145","1110":"1110","1231":"1231","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England","Hungerford, Somerset, England":"Hungerford, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hungerford,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hungerford (Berkshire), from Old English <i>hungor</i> ‘hunger’, here probably denoting unproductive land, + <i>ford</i>. This surname has been established in Ireland since the 17th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]},{"name":"Everard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>eofor</i> ‘boar’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. This was reinforced at the time of the Norman Conquest by a Continental Germanic form introduced to Britain by the Normans. The modern given name may be a transferred use of the surname, but it was in regular use in the Digby family of Rutland from the 15th to the 17th centuries, probably as a survival of the Norman name. It alternated in this family with   Kenelm ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Everard de Hungerford, II was born in 1110, in Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England, his father, Walter Nicholas De Hungerford I, was 30 and his mother, Wife Nicholas, was 30. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth de Heytesbury. He died in 1200, in his hometown, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1110–1200":"1110–1200","1112–Female":"1112–Surnud","1145–1231":"1145–1231","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1112":"1112","1145?":"1145","1110":"1110","1231":"1231","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England","Hungerford, Somerset, England":"Hungerford, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1110–1200":"1110–1200","1112–Female":"1112–Kuollut","1145–1231":"1145–1231","1080–Male":"1080–Kuollut","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1112":"1112","1145?":"1145","1110":"1110","1231":"1231","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England","Hungerford, Somerset, England":"Hungerford, Somerset, England"},"fr":{"1110–1200":"1110–1200","1112–Female":"1112–Décédée","1145–1231":"1145–1231","1080–Male":"1080–Décédé","1080–Female":"1080–Décédée","1080":"1080","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1112":"1112","1145?":"1145","1110":"1110","1231":"1231","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, Angleterre","Hungerford, Somerset, England":"Hungerford, Somerset, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Walter Everard de Hungerford, II est né en 1110, à Heytesbury, Wiltshire, Angleterre, son père, Walter Nicholas De Hungerford I, avait 30 ans et sa mère, Wife Nicholas, avait 30 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Elizabeth de Heytesbury. Il est décédé en 1200, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 90 ans."},"de":{"1110–1200":"1110–1200","1112–Female":"1112–Verstorben","1145–1231":"1145–1231","1080–Male":"1080–Verstorben","1080–Female":"1080–Verstorben","1080":"1080","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1112":"1112","1145?":"1145","1110":"1110","1231":"1231","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England","Hungerford, Somerset, England":"Hungerford, Somerset, England","lifeSummary":"Als Walter Everard d